The Great Tech Reset: A Data Story of Layoffs (2020-2023)
What This Project Is About
Remember when every tech company wanted to grow as fast as possible, no matter the cost? That era ended. When the economy changed, investors stopped asking "How big can you get?" and started asking "How much money do you actually make?"
I analyzed over 2,000 layoff announcements from companies around the world to understand who got hurt most when the party stopped.
________________________________________
What the Numbers Revealed
Finding #1: Big Money Didn't Save Anyone
The Myth: If you raise a billion dollars, you're safe.
The Reality: Some of the most famous failures in my dataset had more cash than 99% of companies ever will. Quibi raised $1.8 billion and still shut down. BlockFi raised $1 billion and collapsed anyway.
The Pattern: Companies that needed constant cash to survive—like media startups, crypto platforms, and food delivery services—were the first to go under. Money delayed the crash but couldn't prevent it.
Simple Truth: Raising a lot of money is like filling a gas tank. If your car gets two miles per gallon, you're still not going far.
________________________________________
Finding #2: January 2023 Was the Worst Month Ever
The Timeline: Everyone thought layoffs would happen fast and end fast. The data tells a different story.
The Numbers:
•	March 2020 (pandemic shock): around 28,000 tech workers laid off
•	January 2023: over 84,700 tech workers laid off
That's a 300% increase nearly three years after COVID began.
Why This Matters: The "Tech Winter" wasn't a sudden freeze. It was a slow, creeping cold that eventually became a blizzard. Companies held on as long as they could, then cut deeper than anyone expected.
Simple Truth: The worst was not the beginning. It came much later.
________________________________________
Finding #3: How Much Money You Raised Determined How You Laid People Off
I grouped companies into three buckets based on funding. The differences were striking.
The Small Startups (raised less than $50 million)
•	Average layoff: 1 out of every 3 employees
•	These companies ran lean already, but when trouble hit, they had no cushion. They either cut deep or died completely.
The Mid-Tier Companies (raised $50 million to $500 million)
•	Average layoff: about 1 out of every 5 employees
•	They had room to maneuver but still felt the squeeze.
The Giants (raised more than $500 million)
•	Average layoff: about 1 out of every 7 employees
•	They cut less aggressively as a percentage, but here's the catch: because these companies were enormous, their "smaller" cuts added up to over 1.1 million jobs lost.
Simple Truth: Startups cut because they had to survive. Giants cut because they had to impress investors. The result was the same for the people packing up their desks.
